[{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Lenard–Bernstein-operator-(2D)","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"The Lenard–Bernstein (LB) operator is a model collision operator that relaxes a distribution towards a Maxwellian. Its conservative (\"modified\") form — used here — adds drift terms so that momentum and energy are conserved alongside mass, which makes the operator nonlinear through its dependence on the moments of the distribution. This page documents the structure-preserving particle discretisation that lives at the repository root (main_LB.jl, functions.jl, MantisWrappers.jl, Parameters.jl, parameters_LB*.jl). The construction follows Jeyakumar et al. (2024), written here in 2D velocity space.","title":"Lenard–Bernstein operator (2D)"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Continuous-operator","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"For a single species with density f_s(mathbfv) and collision frequency nu, the operator is written in advective (continuity) form\n\npartial_t f_s = nabla_mathbf vcdotbig(mathbf a f_sbig)\nqquad\nmathbf a = nuleft(fracnabla_mathbf v f_sf_s + mathbf A + Bmathbf vright)\n\nwhere mathbf AinmathbbR^2 and BinmathbbR are Lagrange multipliers fixed by the conservation constraints. The fixed point of the flow is the Maxwellian for which nablalog f_s + mathbf A + Bmathbf v = 0, and the entropy H = -int f_slog f_smathrm dmathbf v increases monotonically (H-theorem).","title":"Continuous operator"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Particle-representation","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"The density is carried by a weighted Dirac measure,\n\nf_s(mathbf v) approx sum_alpha w_alphadelta(mathbf v - mathbf v_alpha)\n\nwith fixed weights w_alpha and moving markers mathbf v_alpha. By continuity each marker is advected by dotmathbf v_alpha = -mathbf a:\n\ndotmathbf v_alpha\n  = -nuleft(fracnabla f_s(mathbf v_alpha)f_s(mathbf v_alpha)\n              + mathbf A + Bmathbf v_alpharight)\n\nIn the pure-heat limit mathbf A = B = 0 this is drift down the log-density gradient — diffusion that increases H.","title":"Particle representation"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Finite-element-density-and-the-gradient","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"To evaluate nabla f_s  f_s pointwise, a smooth density is reconstructed from the markers by an L^2 projection onto a tensor-product B-spline space X^0 (degree P_DEG, regularity K_REG) on an anisotropic, possibly non-uniform mesh with breakpoints bp1, bp2. The projection solves the mass system\n\nMmathbf c = mathbf bqquad\nb_i = sum_alpha w_alphavarphi_i(mathbf v_alpha)\n\nwith the mass matrix prefactored once (l2_project!). The per-marker log-gradient mathbf g_alpha = nabla f_s(mathbf v_alpha)f_s(mathbf v_alpha) is then evaluated from the coefficients (eval_loggrad_at_particles!). Each component is clamped to pmG_MAX so that a Gibbs undershoot driving f_sto 0^+ cannot make 1f_s blow up the implicit solve; conservation stays exact because the multipliers are solved from the clamped gradient.","title":"Finite-element density and the gradient"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Exact-discrete-conservation","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"The multipliers mathbf A=(A_1A_2) and B are chosen so that the discrete momentum sum_alpha w_alphadotmathbf v_alpha and energy sum_alpha w_alphamathbf v_alphacdotdotmathbf v_alpha vanish. With the raw moments\n\nn = sum_alpha w_alphaquad\nU_k = sum_alpha w_alpha v_alpha kquad\nQ = sum_alpha w_alpha mathbf v_alpha^2\n\nand mathbf S_g = sum_alpha w_alpha mathbf g_alpha, P = sum_alpha w_alphamathbf v_alphacdotmathbf g_alpha, this is the symmetric 3times3 system (compute_drift_multipliers)\n\nbeginbmatrix n  0  U_1  0  n  U_2  U_1  U_2  Q endbmatrix\nbeginbmatrix A_1  A_2  B endbmatrix\n= -beginbmatrix S_g1  S_g2  P endbmatrix\n\nSolving it before each velocity update guarantees momentum and energy are conserved to round-off independent of mesh resolution or time step.","title":"Exact discrete conservation"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Time-integration","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"The markers are advanced with the implicit midpoint rule, which preserves the conservation structure. Each step solves the fixed-point map\n\nmathbf v^n+1 = mathbf v^n\n  + Delta tdotmathbf vleft(tfrac12(mathbf v^n+mathbf v^n+1)right)\n\nby Picard iteration, optionally accelerated by Anderson mixing (step_anderson!) with damping decay and a stagnation-aware early exit. The projection–gradient–multiplier–update sequence is re-evaluated at the midpoint inside every iteration.","title":"Time integration"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Diagnostics","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"Streamed to conservation_history_<suffix>.csv every step:\n\nentropy H_h = -int f_slog f_smathrm dmathbf v (compute_entropy),\nenergy and momentum (should be flat to round-off),\ninner-iteration count and residual lVert G(mathbf v)-mathbf vrVert_2,\nprojection error lVert f_s - f_prVert_2 against the element-constant histogram density (compute_fs_minus_fp_l2),\nnegative-part L^1 norm intmax(-f_s0)mathrm dmathbf v probing Gibbs undershoot (compute_negative_part_l1).","title":"Diagnostics"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#Running","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"julia --project=. main_LB.jl parameters_LB2D_v3.jl\n\nSee the README for presets, overrides, checkpoint/resume and output formats.","title":"Running"},{"category":"section","location":"lenard_bernstein/#References","page":"Lenard–Bernstein (2D)","text":"S. Jeyakumar, M. Kraus, M. J. Hole, and D. Pfefferlé, A structure-preserving particle discretisation for the Lenard-Bernstein collision operator, arXiv:2309.16894 (2024).","title":"References"},{"category":"section","location":"#CollisionOperators","page":"Home","text":"Documentation for CollisionOperators.\n\n","title":"CollisionOperators"}]
